The paper deals with preventing fake or duplicate e-identities from joining an e-community, which is a problem related to computer security (cs.CR). The use of a trust graph to limit the penetration of Byzantines (fake identities and their corrupt perpetrators) involves social networks and graph theory (cs.SI, cs.DS). The paper also discusses the use of consensus protocols and democratic governance, which are topics related to systems and control (cs.SY). Finally, the paper mentions the use of graph conductance as a key tool, which is a topic related to graph theory (cs.GT).
